<chapter xml:id="ch-polygons" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Exploring Polygons and Other Figures on the Plane</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
        In <xref ref="sec-intro-explore"/>, we introduced two basic 
        principles about area, 
        <xref ref="principle-arearect"/> and 
        <xref ref="principle-areasums"/>. In <xref ref="sec-intro-apply"/>, we 
        added another principle  <xref ref="principle-addlengths"/> as well as 
        a long list of common vocabulary terms. 
    </p>
    <aside>
      <p>
        To view the statements of the earlier principles, 
        click on each corresponding link.
      </p>
    </aside>
    <p>
      Before we continue, it will be useful to define what it means for two
      polygons to be congruent:
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-congruent-polygon">
      <idx><h>congruent</h><h>polygon</h></idx>
      <idx><h>corresponding</h><h>sides</h></idx>
      <idx><h>corresponding</h><h>angles</h></idx>
      <notation>
        <usage> <m>\cong</m></usage>
        <description>congruent</description>
      </notation>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Two polygons are said to be <term>congruent</term> if they satisfy
          all of the following:
          <ul marker="disc">
            <li>
              <p>
                The polygons have the same number of sides.
              </p>
              <p>
                Corresponding sides have the same length.
              </p>
              <p>
                Corresponding angles have the same measure.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
          As an example, consider a pair of convex quadrilaterals, <m>ABCD</m> and
          <m>EFGH</m>. We would say <m>ABCD</m> is <term>congruent to</term>
          <m>EFGH</m>, written <m>ABCD\cong EFGH</m> if all of the following
          were true: <m>AB=EF</m>, <m>BC=FG</m>, <m>CD=GH</m>, <m>DA=HE</m>,
          <m>m(\angle ABC)=m(\angle EFG)</m>, <m>m(\angle BCD)=m(\angle FGH)</m>,
          <m>m(\angle CDA)=m(\angle GHE)</m>, and <m>m(\angle DAB)=m(\angle HEF)</m>.
          Note how the labeling of the quadrilaterals' vertices identifies the pairs
          of corresponding sides and the pairs of corresponding angles.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      This leads us to another Principle that we will accept as intuitively obvious:
    </p>
    <!--Prove later?-->
    <principle xml:id="principle-area-of-congruent-figs">
      <title>Area of Congruent Polygons</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If two polygons are congruent, then they have the same area.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </principle>
    <p>
      In this chapter, we will show how these principles lead to the area formulas 
      for other polygons. We will also use our knowledge of area to show why the 
      Pythagorean Theorem holds. While you may already have these area formulas and
      the Pythagorean Theorem memorized, you will soon have first-hand knowledge 
      of why they hold and how they fit with basic principles.
    </p>
  </introduction>  
